{"BR": {"BR_id": "12181", "BR_author": "LinxiFan", "BRopenT": "2020-11-19T23:30:40Z", "BRcloseT": "2020-11-30T06:15:55Z", "BR_text": {"BRsummary": "Ray doesn't allow \"actor=\" kwarg", "BRdescription": "\n Ray v1.0\n <denchmark-code>import ray\n \n @ray.remote\n class Hello:\n     def __init__(self, actor):\n         pass\n \n ray.init()\n \n hello = Hello.remote(10)  # works\n hello = Hello.remote(actor=10)  # fails\n </denchmark-code>\n \n Ray doesn't allow \"actor=\" keyword argument. Error message: actor_method_executor() got multiple values for argument 'actor'.\n I believe the internal variable \"actor\" should be renamed to _actor to avoid the conflict with user API.\n \n  I have verified my script runs in a clean environment and reproduces the issue.\n  I have verified the issue also occurs with the latest wheels.\n \n \t"}, "comments": {"comments_0": {"comment_id": 1, "comment_author": "LinxiFan", "commentT": "2020-11-20T14:20:19Z", "comment_text": "\n \t\tcc <denchmark-link:https://github.com/ericl>@ericl</denchmark-link>\n \n \t\t"}, "comments_1": {"comment_id": 2, "comment_author": "LinxiFan", "commentT": "2020-11-20T18:54:25Z", "comment_text": "\n \t\t<denchmark-link:https://github.com/ericl>@ericl</denchmark-link>\n  Should we change the argument to something else? haha\n \t\t"}, "comments_2": {"comment_id": 3, "comment_author": "LinxiFan", "commentT": "2020-11-20T19:27:39Z", "comment_text": "\n \t\tactor= is a very common term in reinforcement learning, so it'd be great to avoid the conflict. Thanks!\n \t\t"}, "comments_3": {"comment_id": 4, "comment_author": "LinxiFan", "commentT": "2020-11-22T08:50:39Z", "comment_text": "\n \t\tCreated a patch <denchmark-link:https://github.com/ray-project/ray/issues/12181>#12181</denchmark-link>\n \n \t\t"}, "comments_4": {"comment_id": 5, "comment_author": "LinxiFan", "commentT": "2020-11-30T06:16:01Z", "comment_text": "\n \t\tThis should be fixed.\n \t\t"}}}, "commit": {"commit_id": "91d54ef621e16fc69e7f86800ded3